<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1886-07-31T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1886-07-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="270" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d270">
                        <head>No. 266.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Woodbury</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-07-31"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 31,
                                1886</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I beg to acknowledge your letter of
                            yesterday accompanied by the affidavit of Alexander McDonald and eleven
                            others, members of the crew of the schooner Thomas F. Bayard, of
                            Gloucester, stating the refusal of the local officials at Bonne Bay,
                            Newfoundland, to permit fishing or the purchase of bait on that
                            coast.</p>
                        <p>The subject to which this paper relates received due attention yesterday,
                            as you were advised.</p>
                        <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                        <closer><signed>T. F. BAYARD.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>